Introduction¶

Fake news is a broad term and in this project our focus will be on covid-19 tweets and online articles whether the infomation presented to the reader is fake or real. In this notebook, we will leverage the prepared datasets which can be found in the data preparation notebook in this project attachments to create models that will help us predict whether the tweet you would like to read or the article you are interested in reading tend to be reliable or fake.

Problem understanding¶

News can be in many different forms. For example, Newspapers, Magazines, TV and radio, Internet, News agencies and Alternative media. Now, there are some businesses that try to promote their products or to advertise a product and some publish fake, attractive or charming news as 'clickbait' and we tend to be curious when it comes to unusual things and so we read / check the content. For instance, in 1835 newspaper company claimed that they have found out creates live in moon (humans with wings) here is link for full article. That as a consequence allowed the company to be more popular which allowed them to promote and advertise more. Now this is one of the reasons why would certain group of people / a person publish fake news or misleading information. However, the influnce on the reader is usually harmful. For example, it could be that fake news regards healthy food suggest or recommend some types of food for people who suffer from kind of illness and if reader followed the suggestions that could be in fact harmful for them since news were fake in the first place. There are more scenarios obviously but this is where the problem lies. Fake news in general are published for the sake of obtaining profit most of the time and readers might believe misleading information which could influence their decisions.

In this research though, the focus will be on the news of covid-19 topic (tweets) and various topics of fake, legit articles published on the internet.

Explanation of the loaded libraries¶

  • pandas is a fast, powerful, flexible and easy to use open source data analysis and manipulation tool, built on top of the Python programming language.
  • NumPy is the fundamental package for scientific computing in Python. It is a Python library that provides a multidimensional array object, various derived objects (such as masked arrays and matrices), and an assortment of routines for fast operations on arrays, including mathematical, logical, shape manipulation, sorting, selecting, I/O, discrete Fourier transforms, basic linear algebra, basic statistical operations, random simulation and much more.
  • Matplotlib is a plotting library for the Python programming language and its numerical mathematics extension NumPy.
  • Seaborn is a data visualization library built on top of matplotlib and closely integrated with pandas data structures in Python.
  • TfidfVectorizer - It is a technique used for natural language processing, that transforms text to feature vectors that can be used as input to the estimator.
  • train_test_split is a function in Sklearn model selection for splitting data arrays into two subsets: for training data and for testing data.
  • GridSearchCV is a library function that is a member of sklearn's model_selection package. It helps to loop through predefined hyperparameters and fit your estimator (model) on your training set. So, in the end, you can select the best parameters from the listed hyperparameters.
  • The purpose of the pipeline is to assemble several steps that can be cross-validated together while setting different parameters.
  • The multinomial Naive Bayes classifier is suitable for classification with discrete features (e.g., word counts for text classification)
  • SGDClassifier is a linear classifier (by default in sklearn it is a linear SVM) that uses SGD for training (that is, looking for the minima of the loss using SGD). According to the documentation: SGDClassifier is a Linear classifiers (SVM, logistic regression, a.o.) with SGD training.
  • Random Forest is a robust machine learning algorithm that can be used for a variety of tasks including regression and classification.
  • DecisionTreeClassifier is a class capable of performing multi-class classification on a dataset
  • Classification report Text summary of the precision, recall, F1 score for each class
  • Confusion matrix, also known as an error matrix, is a specific table layout that allows visualization of the performance of an algorithm, typically a supervised learning one
  • The cross_val_score() function will be used to perform the evaluation, taking the dataset and cross-validation configuration and returning a list of scores calculated for each fold

Data description¶

covid19_tweets is a dataset that contains tweets taken from twitter reagrding covid 19 period in 2021. The dataset owner has classified the tweets in label coumn as fake or real. The data has been explored and the sources of the data are available in the proposal and the EDA part of data collection. The data has also been prepared in the preparation notebook. In general the data currently contains text that has been processed so all text lowered, expanded contractions (example, it's --> it is), emojis, digits, hyperlinks, hashtags and stop words has been removed. Lastly, all words have been reversed back to its orginal form using lemmatization technique (example, went --> go, gone --> go).

online_articles is a dataset that contains fake articles that have been taken from kaggle and merged with real articles taken from allsides. The dataset owner has merged both dataset and published the finalized dataset which is used in this project dataset article,github link. The data has been explored and the sources of the data are available in the proposal and the EDA part of data collection. The data has also been prepared in the preparation notebook. In general the data currently contains text that has been processed so all text lowered, expanded contractions (example, it's --> it is), emojis, digits and stop words has been removed. Lastly, all words have been reversed back to its orginal form using lemmatization technique (example, went --> go, gone --> go).

Findings¶

  • We can notice that when the word claim or any of its different forms in the past, present or future have an 18% chance for the that tweet to be fake. While the word test or any of its different forms in the past, present or future have 27% chance for the tweet to be real. In addition, any word that have positive correlation with fake is having negative correlation with real.
  • We can notice that when the word say or any of its different forms in the past, present or future have an 42% chance for the that article to be real. While the word hillary or any of its different forms in the past, present or future have 10% chance for the article to be fake. In addition, any word that have positive correlation with fake is having negative correlation with real.

Feature text extraction¶

Machine Learning algorithms learn from a pre-defined set of features from the training data to produce output for the test data. But the main problem in working with language processing is that machine learning algorithms cannot work on the raw text directly. So, we need some feature extraction techniques to convert text into a matrix(or vector) of features.

Essentially what we are doing here is that, we go through each article/tweet and create vocabulary for each dataset that contain each word and its relevance to the overall corpus of the whole given text. We will be using TfIDF to implement this part.

MultinomialNB model of covid19 tweets 0.897721

Random forest model of covid19 tweets 0.896277
Decision tree model of covid19 tweets 0.840722

After tuning the hyperparameters, pipeline has been used to facilitate the repetitve process of instaniating the model and fit it on the training data. The cross validation has been added and the amount of K folds used is 5. According to the performance of the models it appears that SGDClassifier has the highest cross validation score. Thus, the second model will be the final covid_19 tweets reliability detection model. As I have indicated in the proposal that the recommended natrual language processing models are MultinomialNB and SGDClassifier the average cross valdiation scores of those model are quite high and it makes since this project about natural language processing and working with text in order to classify it. Now the exact reason why SGDClassifier has performed better than the Multinomial model despite both being a recommended model for processing text that I am not sure about but in general both had their parameters tuned to boost their efficeny and increase their potential.

Online articles models¶

In this section, 4 model are going to be instaniated as mentioned in the sub-section decription. We will be using GridSearchCV to tune in hyperparameters and pipeline to repeat process for every model and evaluate the results using confusion matrix report, classification report and cross validation. Each model performance will be taken into account and a reliability chart will be created where each model performance is displayed to helping decision on which model will be selected as final chosen model for covid 19 dataset.

After tuning the hyperparameters, pipeline has been used to facilitate the repetitve process of instaniating the model and fit it on the training data. The cross validation has been added and the amount of K folds used is 5. According to the performance of the models it appears that SGDClassifier has the highest cross validation score. Thus, the second model will be the final model of online article reliability detection. As I have indicated in the proposal that the recommended natrual language processing models are MultinomialNB and SGDClassifier the average cross valdiation scores of those model are quite high and it makes since this project about natural language processing and working with text in order to classify it. Now the exact reason why SGDClassifier has performed better than the Multinomial model despite both being a recommended model for processing text that I am not sure about but in general both had their parameters tuned to boost their efficeny and increase their potential.

Conclusion¶

To wrap up this notebook, we have used the datasets that were produced from the data preparation notebook of phase 2. We have understood basic information about the data we were working with in order to make this notebook almost independent and it is the reader's choice to read the other notebooks for more clarification about the data. Covid 19 tweets dataset and online article dataset both have been cleaned and processed their text with a label available for supervised machine learning. The datasets had roughly about 6000 rows of data in which half of them were fake and the other reliable and that indiciated the balance of the data. We visualized the relationship between length of each article/tweet with the reliablity and derived that about 14% of the time if the text have more keywords the content of the news tend to be real/reliable. In addition we visualized the top important words of fake and real covid19 tweets/online articles and have seen the correlation between them, generally if a word correlate positively with the real news it tends to have negative correlation with fake news. We prepared the data by first splitting them into training and testing data then used tf-idf because we are working with text and that is logical preparation for natural language processing before training a model. Speaking of models, We have created 4 models for each dataset (articles and covid19 tweets). We have applied hyperparameters tuning with GridSearchCV and used pipeline to facilitate the process that each model go through. We have applied cross validation and seen classification and confusion matrix as our evaluation metrics. Lastly we noticed that SGDClassifier model had the best performed overall and therefore we decided to use it as our final model.
